The Thompson's serious shortcomings were its weight, reduced accuracy at a distance of more than 45 m and insufficient penetration power of the 45 caliber cartridge. Harry Boland, a member of the House of Representatives of the Irish Republic, was one of those who acquired the Thompsons for the needs of the Irish Republican Army - for the first time they were tested by the IRA's West Cork Brigade under the command of Tom Barry in the presence of Michael Collins[38]. what was not confiscated fell into the hands of the IRA in transit through Liverpool and was used in the last month of the Irish War of Independence[39]. .